Hello nlmixr development team,

I am trying out nlmixr for the first time and have an issue. I have a multi dose data set (simulated) for a single subject. I am fixing most of the parameters and trying to estimate one parameter only. I do not need to BSV random effect. I am using nlme_ode() function and am getting the following error message.  I believe it is looking for random effect parameters formula. Any suggestions?

Also, how do I mention residual error structure in this type of model?

I am not sure how to attach a dataset here. I can send it in email if needed.

Thanks,
Krina

Model Code:

```
ode <- "
CL=0.111;
Vmax=11.9;
Km=33.9;
V1=2.91;
Q=0.445;
V2=3.06;
C1 = centr/V1;
C2 = peri/V2;
d/dt(depot) = -KA*depot;
d/dt(centr) = KA*depot - CL*C1 - Vmax*C1/(Km+C1) - Q*C1 + Q*C2;
d/dt(peri)  = Q*C1 - Q*C2;
"
specs <- list(fixed=lKA~1, start=c(KA=-0.916))

mypar <- function(lKA) {KA=exp(lKA)}

fit <- nlme_ode(fitdata, ode, par_model=specs, par_trans=mypar, response="C1")
```

**_Error in reStruct(random, REML = REML, data = NULL) : 
  'object' must be a list or a formula_**

If I update the specs with the following, it works
`specs <- list(fixed=lKA~1, random=lKA~1, start=c(KA=-0.916))`

I have been unable to specify fixed covariates in this format.  I know this has been mentioned here: https://github.com/nlmixrdevelopment/nlmixr/issues/7

However I was wondering if there was a workaround for this. I have tried specifying the covariate as a column in my data set, but this only works with with the nlme estimation method. As mentioned previously you can also not reference a numerical value in the model section. Below is my model. Specifically, I am trying to fix WTexpVC and SEXpropCL to 1 and 0.45 respectively, while allowing the other covariates to be estimated. In this example, logWTFrac is equal to log(WT/MedianWT) and is a column in my dataset

```R
func_2cmt_SAEM <- function(){
  ini({
    #Initials Estimates
    lVc <- log(100) #log Vc (L)
    lVp <- log(200) #log Vp (L)
    lCl <- log(10) #log Cl (L/hr)
    lQ <- log(250) #log between CMT clearnace (L/hr)
    lKa <- log(0.540) #log Ka (1/hr)
    #Covariates
    WTexpCL <- 0.75
    WTexpVC <- 0.75
    WTexpVP <- 0.75
    SEXpropCL <- 0.45
    ASUUMpropVC <- 0.75
    #Error
    prop.err <- c(0,0.2,1)
    eta.Vc ~ 0.3 
    eta.Vp ~ 0.3
    eta.Cl ~ 0.3
    eta.Q  ~ 0.3
    eta.Ka ~ 0.2 # BSV Ka
  })
  model({ 
    Vc <- exp(lVc + eta.Vc + WTexpVC*logWTFrac + ASUUMpropVC*ASUUM);
    Vp <- exp(lVp + eta.Vp + WTexpVP*logWTFrac);
    Cl <- exp(lCl + eta.Cl + WTexpCL*logWTFrac + SEXpropCL*SEXF);
   
    Q <- exp(lQ + eta.Q);
    Ka <- exp(lKa + eta.Ka);
    K23 <- Q / Vc;
    K32 <- Q / Vp;
    Kel <- Cl / Vc;
    d/dt(depot)  = -Ka*depot; #CMT 1
    d/dt(centr)  =  Ka*depot - K23*centr + K32*periph - Kel*centr; #CMT 2
    d/dt(periph) =  K23*centr - K32*periph; #CMT 3
    
    cp = centr/Vc;
    cp ~ prop(prop.err);
  })}
```

Any workaround method would be greatly appreciated

Such as with the following model:
```R
    ExponentialModelPop <- function() {
      ini({
        tx10 <- 0   # Log x0
        ta <- 0     # Log a
        add.err <- 1
      })
      model({
        a <- exp( ta )
        x10 <- exp( tx10 )
        x1(0) = x10
        d/dt(x1) = a*x1
        Volume = x1
        Volume ~ add(add.err)
      })
    }
```

(With `est="saem"`, `nlmixr` returns the error `SAEM requires all ETAS to be mu-referenced`.)

I understand that `dynmodel` would be the natural choice here, however, I have multiple subject with different dosings, so I can't use that (if my understanding is correct!). I nevertheless want to fit one, "global" model.

I'm a beginner as R user. And excuse my poor English.
Now I'd like to validate the result by nlmixr and SAS, using theophylline data.
So, I'm trying the description "pred = dose * ke * ka * (exp(-ke * time)-exp(-ka * time))/cl/(ka-ke)" of SAS sample on nlmixr.

How should I modify "cp" of nlmixr to get the same description of SAS?
I'd like to get the description like above the same SAS description "pred = dose * ke * ka * (exp(-ke * time)-exp(-ka * time))/cl/(ka-ke)".
Could you please give me some advice?

***nlmixr sample program**
[Running PK models with nlmixr](https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/nlmixr/vignettes/running_nlmixr.html)
```R
one.compartment.saem <- function() {
    ini({
        tka <- .5   # Log Ka
        tcl <- -3.2 # Log Cl
        tv <- -1    # Log V
        eta.ka ~ 1
        eta.cl ~ 2
        eta.v ~ 1
        add.err <- 0.1
    })
    model({
        ka <- exp(tka + eta.ka)
        cl <- exp(tcl + eta.cl)
        v <- exp(tv + eta.v)
        d/dt(depot) = -ka * depot
        d/dt(center) = ka * depot - cl / v * center
        cp = center / v 
        cp ~ add(add.err)
    })
}
```
***SAS sample program**
[Example 61.1 One-Compartment Model with Pharmacokinetic Data](https://support.sas.com/documentation/cdl/en/statug/63033/HTML/default/viewer.htm#statug_nlmixed_sect039.htm)
```sas
proc nlmixed data=theoph;
      parms beta1=-3.22 beta2=0.47 beta3=-2.45 
            s2b1 =0.03  cb12 =0    s2b2 =0.4 s2=0.5;
      cl   = exp(beta1 + b1);
      ka   = exp(beta2 + b2);
      ke   = exp(beta3);
      pred = dose * ke * ka * (exp(-ke * time)-exp(-ka * time))/cl/(ka-ke);
      model conc ~ normal(pred,s2);
      random b1 b2 ~ normal([0,0],[s2b1,cb12,s2b2]) subject=subject;
   run;

```

